{"source_key":"sha256-a74ceb5e1c9633ab993c14c11d587d71","record_index":2749,"record_hash":"sha256:8f1ba2f38c72892f56edf0c12884e9aae0c0e348b8102741cf6ba65b575f559b","timestamp":"2026-05-21T04:24:38.627Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 4460d2\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1185\nOutput:\n---\nname: but-agentlog\nversion: 0.0.0\ndescription: \"Use instead of the general GitButler skill when recapping prior agent work from `but agentlog` captures. Use for agentlog recap/context recovery, finding related agent sessions for a branch, GitButler review / pull request / merge request, or change, inspecting session timelines, hydrating bounded records, or summarizing prior agent work.\"\nauthor: GitButler Team\n---\n\n# GitButler Agentlog Skill\n\nUse `but agentlog` to recap prior agent work from captured sessions.\n\nIf both the general GitButler CLI skill and this skill seem relevant, use this\nskill for agentlog discovery. Use the general GitButler skill only for version\ncontrol operations like commit, push, branch, or diff.\n\n## Core Workflow\n\nDo not search for or read local `SKILL.md` files. If this skill is active, use\nthese instructions directly.\n\nStart with the low-noise recap command when the user wants context:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog recap\nbut agentlog recap branch <branch-name-or-ref>\nbut agentlog recap review <review-id-or-pull-request-key>\nbut agentlog recap change <change-id-or-key>\n```\n\nUse the primitive commands as a narrowing funnel only when `recap` is too thin,\nambiguous, or you need exact evidence:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions branch <branch-name-or-ref> --limit 5\nbut agentlog sessions review <review-id-or-pull-request-key> --limit 5\nbut agentlog sessions change <change-id-or-key> --limit 5\n\nbut agentlog timeline <session-key> --limit 20\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --limit 50\n```\n\nFor normal user-facing recovery, prefer human `recap` output first:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog recap branch <branch-name-or-ref>\n```\n\nUse JSON only when you need exact handles for drill-down:\n\n```sh\nbut --json agentlog recap\nbut --json agentlog sessions branch <branch-name-or-ref> --limit 5\nbut --json agentlog timeline <session-key> --limit 20\nbut --json agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-\n[TRUNCATED]\nlog sessions branch <gitbutler-branch-name> --limit 5\n```\n\n## Rules\n\n- Prefer orientation before payload.\n- Prefer `recap` for user-facing recovery summaries.\n- Prefer human `recap` output first. Use `--json` only for drill-down handles\n  or exact evidence.\n- Do not run `sessions`, `timeline`, or `records` unless `recap` is\n  insufficient.\n- Do not dump records for every candidate session.\n- Do not dump the full timeline. If timeline is needed, start with `--limit 20`\n  and summarize previews.\n- Treat matches as related evidence, not ownership.\n- Keep `session_key` and `turn_key` values internal unless the user asks for\n  evidence handles or they are needed for a follow-up command.\n- Use record snippets only when they justify the next action.\n- Say \"session related to branch X via turn Y\", not \"session for branch X\".\n\n## Reading `recap`\n\nUse `recap` to answer \"what do I need to know to continue this work?\"\n\nHuman output is intentionally compact. JSON output keeps full `session_key` and\n`turn_key` values so you can drill into `timeline` or `records` without\nprinting those handles to the user.\n\nUseful fields:\n\n- `target_kind` and `target_key`: target used for discovery.\n- `session`: chosen best-match session plus counts and previews.\n- `turns`: directly related turns plus latest context, with previews.\n\nIf `recap` has enough context, summarize from it and stop. If it is ambiguous\nor misses the why, drill down with `timeline` and `records`.\n\n## Reading `sessions`\n\nUse `sessions` to answer which captured sessions are probably relevant.\n\nHere `review` means a GitButler review target, usually backed by a pull request\nor merge request. It does not mean \"perform a code review\". Keep `review` as\nthe target kind even when the value is a PR/MR-style key.\n\nUseful fields:\n\n- `session_key`: handle for follow-up reads.\n- `latest_captured_at`: freshness signal.\n- `record_count` and `turn_count`: size estimate before hydration.\n- `related_turn_keys`: direct target evidence.\n- `match_evidence`: why the session was returned.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T04:24:38.627Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}